Yet Avan- cius did borrow largely, very largely from Marullus, especially in the case of interpolated verses made by the latter. How is this to be explainedl Evidently even before his death Marullus' labours on Lucretius were known3 and probably there were more copies than one of these, the one not always agreeing with the other. On this point compare notes l to 1 551-627, where Candidus makes some perverse transpositions oi verses, on the authority of Marullus he says in his note at the end, but the learned annotator of one of the laurentian mss. states that some put tol-564 after 576, and adds ‘verum Marullo parum referre videtur quo modo legatur’. This annotator and Avancius Pius Candidus Gitanius can hardly all have had the same copyt perhaps all were different. Avan- cius then may have had his notes in the very copy of Ven. on which he formed his text, and may have looked on them as public property which he might make use of without acknowledgment according to the prac- tice of the time3 for neither Pius nor Candidus acknowledges in his turn what he got from Avancius3 nor does Naugerius the editor os Ald. 2 say a syllable oi Candidus whose edition he copied with few variations. ¹

But Lachmann to 111 98 cites in proof of his charge that Avancius ’ was a dishonest plagiary three interpolated verses which doubtless were composed by Marullus and are corruptly given in Ald l. In notes l to 111 98 I have attempted to shew from Gifanius that Marullus perhaps wrote putarit, and that Avancius intended to read the same: Avancius was probably as good a Latin scholar as Marullus, if less versed in Lucretius. In the line inserted after 1v102 multoc for multae may be an error of the printer or an oversight of Avancius. In that inserted after 1v 532 there can be little doubt that he purposely wrote cuis, imagining that oria was a plural. The correcting of texts was then in its infancy, and Avancius had so grievous a task before him in making sense out of the monstrously corrupted Venice edition, that much must in fairness be excused: we cannot tell what were the exact relations
